          "body": "The psalm's theological argument begins in verses 4-6 with a meditation on what Yahweh is *not* pleased by, who *cannot* stand before Him, whom He *hates*, whom He *destroys*, and whom He *abhors*. The accumulation is striking — five divine responses to wickedness in three verses. God is not neutral toward evil; He is constitutively opposed to it. *Resah* (wickedness) and *ra* (evil) cannot dwell *with* Him (5:4). The boastful (*halal*) cannot stand *before His eyes* (5:5). Liars are destroyed (5:6). The man of bloodshed and deceit is *abhorred* (*taav*, the strongest revulsion word in the Hebrew vocabulary). This is not incidental divine psychology — it is the theological foundation of the entire psalm. Why does David pray? Because the God he addresses has a character that is categorically opposed to the kind of enemy David faces. The enemies are not a problem David and God happen to share; they are rebels against the very nature of Yahweh. Derek Kidner (Psalms 1-72, Tyndale OT Commentary) notes that the psalm's 'moral polarities are not David's personal preferences but reflections of what God is.' The character of God is the only stable ground for prayer in a morally chaotic world."
