          "title": "The anatomy of deceit: enemies whose speech is a tomb (5:8-10)",
          "body": "Having entered the temple and worshiped, David returns to the world where the enemies operate and asks for two things: divine guidance (5:8) and divine judgment (5:10). The request for guidance is grounded in the enemy's character, exposed in the psalm's most graphically anatomical verse (5:9): nothing *reliable* in their speech (*ayin kun* — there is no steadiness, no established word); their inward part (*qerev*) is destruction (*havvah*) itself; their throat is an open grave; their tongue makes things smooth (*chalaq*). Paul quotes verse 9a in Romans 3:13 as evidence of universal human sin's effect on speech — 'Their throat is an open sepulcher.' The four-part anatomy (mouth / inward part / throat / tongue) anatomizes the enemy's speech-system from inside to outside: what is within is destruction; what comes out is lethal; the words themselves are flattery concealing a tomb. No wonder David needs God to make his path straight (5:8) — navigating this environment without divine guidance is navigating a minefield. The imprecation of verse 10 is the logical consequence: David asks God to hold them guilty by their own devices and thrust them out because their rebellion is against *Yahweh* (5:10). The imprecation is not personal revenge but a petition for divine justice — God's cause, not David's ego, is the stated ground."
